                            jump to other results
                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" hclass="sense" id="andrew_sng_1" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" hclass="sensetop" htag="span"><span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">(1st century AD) the <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/patron-saint" title="patron saint definition"><span class="ndv">patron saint</span></a> of Scotland. He was one of the 12 <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/apostle#apostle_sng_1" title="Apostles definition"><span class="ndv">Apostles</span></a>, the brother of St Peter. He became the patron saint of the <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/pict" title="Picts definition"><span class="ndv">Picts</span></a> in the 8th century, when, it is thought, his bones were brought to a town on the east coast of Scotland, later called <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/st-andrews" title="St Andrews definition"><span class="ndv">St Andrews</span></a>. According to tradition, he was killed in Greece on a cross in the shape of an X, and so this cross is on the Scottish flag. Andrew is also the patron saint of Greece and Russia.</span></span>    <div id="ring-links-box">
